s into place. Even today, historians are not completely sure how the Egyptians managed to build something so enormous with the tools they had.","qs":[{"q":"Why was the Great Pyramid built?","opts":["As a temple","As a tomb for Pharaoh Khufu","As a palace"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says 'It was built as a tomb for Pharaoh Khufu'."},{"q":"How many stone blocks were used?","opts":["About 1 million","About 2.3 million","About 5 million"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says 'about 2.3 million stone blocks'."},{"q":"What does the passage tell us about historians today?","opts":["They know exactly how it was built","They are not completely sure how it was built","They think it was built by aliens"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says 'historians are not completely sure how the Egyptians managed to build something so enormous'."}]},{"id":"r2_2","passage":"Octopuses are some of the most intelligent creatures in the ocean. They have three hearts and blue blood. An octopus can change its colour and texture in less than a second to hide from predators. They have been observed using tools, such as carrying coconut shells to use as shelter. Each of their eight arms has its own mini-brain, allowing the arms to act somewhat independently. Some species can even solve simple puzzles and open jars.","qs":[{"q":"How many hearts does an octopus have?","opts":["One","Two","Three"],"cor":2,"exp":"The passage says 'They have three hearts'."},{"q":"Why do octopuses change colour?","opts":["To attract mates","To hide from predators","To find food"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says they change colour 'to hide from predators'."},{"q":"What is special about each arm?","opts":["Each arm has suction cups","Each arm has its own mini-brain","Each arm can regrow"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says 'Each of their eight arms has its own mini-brain'."}]},{"id":"r2_3","passage":"In 1969, Neil Armstrong became the first person to walk on the Moon. He was part of the Apollo 11 mission. When he stepped onto the surface, he said, 'That is one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind.' The astronauts spent about two and a half hours outside the spacecraft. They collected moon rocks and took photographs. The mission showed that space travel was possible and inspired millions of people around the world.","qs":[{"q":"When did Neil Armstrong walk on the Moon?","opts":["1959","1969","1979"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says 'In 1969'."},{"q":"How long did the astronauts spend outside the spacecraft?","opts":["About one hour","About two and a half hours","About five hours"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says 'about two and a half hours'."},{"q":"What effect did the mission have on people?","opts":["It scared them","It inspired millions","It made them angry"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says it 'inspired millions of people around the world'."}]},{"id":"r2_4","passage":"Rainforests cover only about 6% of the Earth's surface, but they contain more than half of the world's plant and animal species. The Amazon Rainforest is the largest, covering parts of nine South American countries. Rainforest trees produce a large amount of the oxygen we breathe. However, rainforests are being cut down at an alarming rate for farming and timber. Scientists warn that destroying rainforests could speed up climate change and cause many species to become extinct.","qs":[{"q":"What percentage of the Earth do rainforests cover?","opts":["About 6%","About 25%","About 50%"],"cor":0,"exp":"The passage says 'about 6% of the Earth's surface'."},{"q":"Why are rainforests being cut down?","opts":["For farming and timber","For building cities","For mining gold"],"cor":0,"exp":"The passage says 'for farming and timber'."},{"q":"What could happen if rainforests are destroyed?","opts":["Nothing much","Climate change could speed up and species could go extinct","The weather would get colder"],"cor":1,"exp":"Scientists warn it 'could speed up climate change and cause many species to become extinct'."}]}],"3":[{"id":"r3_1","passage":"The concept of democracy originated in ancient Athens around the 5th century BC. Unlike modern democracies, Athenian democracy was direct \u2014 citizens voted on laws themselves rather than electing representatives. However, the system was far from inclusive: only adult male citizens could participate, which excluded women, slaves, and foreigners. Despite these limitations, the Athenian model introduced revolutionary ideas about citizen participation and accountability that continue to influence political systems worldwide. Some historians argue that calling it a 'democracy' by modern standards is misleading, given that the majority of the population had no voice.","qs":[{"q":"How did Athenian democracy differ from modern democracy?","opts":["Citizens voted on laws directly instead of electing representatives","It was exactly the same as today","Only the king made decisions"],"cor":0,"exp":"The passage says it was 'direct \u2014 citizens voted on laws themselves rather than electing representatives'."},{"q":"Why do some historians think calling it a 'democracy' is misleading?","opts":["Because it was not in Greece","Because the majority of people had no voice","Because it lasted too long"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says 'the majority of the population had no voice'."},{"q":"What lasting effect did Athenian democracy have?","opts":["None at all","It influenced political systems worldwide","It only affected Greece"],"cor":1,"exp":"The passage says ideas 'continue to influence political systems worldwide'."}]},{"id":"r3_2","passage":"Artificial intelligence has made remarkable progress in recent years, with systems that can write essays, create art, and even diagnose diseases. Supporters argue that AI will revolutionise healthcare, education, and scientific research, potentially solving problems that humans alone cannot. Critics, however, raise concerns about job displacement, privacy, and the possibility of AI systems making biased decisions based on flawed training data. The debate often centres on whether AI should be treated as a tool that humans control or as an autonomous system that makes independent decisions. Finding the right balance between innovation and regulation remains one of the most important challenges of our time.","qs":[{"q":"What concern do critics raise about AI decisions?","opts":["AI is too slow","AI might make biased decisions from flawed training data","AI costs too much"],"cor":1,"exp":"Critics raise concerns about 'AI systems making biased decisions based on flawed training data'."},{"q":"What is the central debate about AI according to the passage?","opts":["Whether AI is real","Whether AI should be a tool humans control or an autonomous system","Whether AI should be banned completely"],"cor":1,"exp":"The debate centres on 'whether AI should be treated as a tool that humans control or as an autonomous system'."},{"q":"What challenge does the passage identify?","opts":["Making AI cheaper","Balancing innovation and regulation","Replacing all human workers"],"cor":1,"exp":"'Finding the right balance between innovation and regulation remains one of the most important challenges'."}]},{"id":"r3_3","passage":"Marie Curie was the first woman to win a Nobel Prize and remains the only person to have won Nobel Prizes in two different sciences \u2014 Physics and Chemistry. Born in Poland in 1867, she moved to Paris to study and eventually discovered two new elements: polonium and radium. Her research on radioactivity laid the groundwork for modern cancer treatments. However, her work came at a personal cost: years of exposure to radiation damaged her health, and she died in 1934 from aplastic anaemia, almost certainly caused by her research. Curie's legacy demonstrates both the extraordinary potential of scientific dedication and the importance of safety in research.","qs":[{"q":"What makes Marie Curie unique in Nobel Prize history?","opts":["She was the youngest winner","She won prizes in two different sciences","She won three prizes"],"cor":1,"exp":"She 'remains the only person to have won Nobel Prizes in two different sciences'."},{"q":"What was the personal cost of Curie's research?","opts":["She lost her funding","Radiation exposure damaged her health and likely caused her death","She had to leave Poland"],"cor":1,"exp":"'Years of exposure to radiation damaged her health, and she died in 1934 from aplastic anaemia'."},{"q":"What two things does Curie's legacy demonstrate?","opts":["Wealth and fame","Scientific potential and the importance of research safety","Speed and efficiency"],"cor":1,"exp":"Her legacy demonstrates 'the extraordinary potential of scientific dedication and the importance of safety in research'."}]}]};
const WP={"1":[{"id":"w1_1","title":"My Favourite Animal","inst":"Write 5 sentences about your favourite animal. Use the steps below to help you.","sc":[{"l":"Step 1: Name your animal","h":"Write: My favourite animal is a _____."},{"l":"Step 2: What does it look like?","h":"Write: It has _____ and _____. It is _____."},{"l":"Step 3: Where does it live?","h":"Write: It lives in _____."},{"l":"Step 4: What does it eat?","h":"Write: It eats _____."},{"l":"Step 5: Why do you like it?","h":"Write: I like it because _____."}],"rub":"Write at least 5 sentences. Start each sentence with a capital letter. End each sentence with a full stop."},{"id":"w1_2","title":"What I Did Today","inst":"Write 5 sentences about what you did today. Use the steps below.","sc":[{"l":"Step 1: Start your day","h":"Write: This morning, I _____."},{"l":"Step 2: Next thing","h":"Write: After that, I _____."},{"l":"Step 3: Something fun","h":"Write: The best part was when I _____."},{"l":"Step 4: How you felt","h":"Write: I felt _____ because _____."},{"l":"Step 5: End your day","h":"Write: Tonight, I will _____."}],"rub":"Write at least 5 sentences. Use time words (this morning, after that, tonight). End each sentence with a full stop."},{"id":"w1_3","title":"My Best Friend","inst":"Write 5 sentences about your best friend.","sc":[{"l":"Step 1: Name them","h":"Write: My best friend is _____."},{"l":"Step 2: Describe them","h":"Write: They are _____ and _____."},{"l":"Step 3: What you do together","h":"Write: We like to _____ together."},{"l":"Step 4: A fun memory","h":"Write: One time, we _____."},{"l":"Step 5: Why they are your friend","h":"Write: They are my best friend because _____."}],"rub":"Write at least 5 sentences. Use capital letters for names. End each sentence with a full stop."},{"id":"w1_4","title":"My Favourite Food","inst":"Write 5 sentences about your favourite food.","sc":[{"l":"Step 1: Name it","h":"Write: My favourite food is _____."},{"l":"Step 2: Describe it","h":"Write: It looks _____ and tastes _____."},{"l":"Step 3: When you eat it","h":"Write: I usually eat it for/when _____."},{"l":"Step 4: Who makes it","h":"Write: _____ makes it for me."},{"l":"Step 5: Why you like it","h":"Write: I like it because _____."}],"rub":"Write at least 5 sentences. Start sentences with capital letters. Use describing words."}],"2":[{"id":"w2_1","title":"A Day at the Beach","inst":"Write a short story (8-10 sentences) about a day at the beach. Follow the plan below.","sc":[{"l":"Opening: Set the scene","h":"When did you go? Who went with you? What was the weather like?"},{"l":"Middle: What happened","h":"What did you do first? What happened next? Was there a problem or surprise?"},{"l":"Ending: How it finished","h":"How did the day end? How did you feel?"}],"rub":"Write 8-10 sentences. Use paragraphs (opening, middle, ending). Include describing words (adjectives). Use correct punctuation (full stops, commas, capital letters)."},{"id":"w2_2","title":"My Dream Holiday","inst":"Write a description (8-10 sentences) of your dream holiday.","sc":[{"l":"Where and why","h":"Where would you go? Why did you choose this place?"},{"l":"What you would do","h":"What activities would you try? What would you see?"},{"l":"Conclusion","h":"Why would this be the perfect holiday?"}],"rub":"Write 8-10 sentences. Use 'would' for imaginary events. Include at least 3 adjectives. Use correct punctuation."},{"id":"w2_3","title":"Should Children Have Homework?","inst":"Write a short opinion piece (8-10 sentences). Give your opinion and explain why.","sc":[{"l":"State your opinion","h":"Do you think children should have homework? Write your view clearly."},{"l":"Give reasons","h":"Give 2-3 reasons that support your opinion. Start with: Firstly... Secondly... Also..."},{"l":"Consider the other side","h":"What might someone who disagrees say? Start with: However, some people think..."},{"l":"Conclusion","h":"Repeat your main opinion. Start with: In conclusion..."}],"rub":"Write 8-10 sentences. State a clear opinion. Give at least 2 reasons. Use linking words (firstly, however, in conclusion). Use correct punctuation."},{"id":"w2_4","title":"A Scary Night","inst":"Write a short story (8-10 sentences) about a scary night.","sc":[{"l":"Set the scene","h":"Where were you? What time was it? What was the weather like?"},{"l":"Build tension","h":"What did you hear or see? How did you feel? What happened next?"},{"l":"Resolution","h":"How did the scary moment end? Was it actually scary?"}],"rub":"Write 8-10 sentences. Use describing words to create atmosphere. Use short sentences for tension. Use correct punctuation."}],"3":[{"id":"w3_1","title":"Should School Uniforms Be Compulsory?","inst":"Write a balanced argument (12-15 sentences) discussing both sides.","sc":[{"l":"Introduction","h":"Introduce the topic. Why is this debated? State that you will look at both sides."},{"l":"Arguments FOR","h":"Give 2-3 reasons supporting school uniforms. Use evidence or examples."},{"l":"Arguments AGAINST","h":"Give 2-3 reasons against school uniforms. Use evidence or examples."},{"l":"Your conclusion","h":"State your own opinion. Which side do you agree with more, and why?"}],"rub":"Write 12-15 sentences. Use formal language. Include arguments for AND against. Use linking phrases (furthermore, on the other hand, in conclusion). Support points with examples. Use correct punctuation throughout."},{"id":"w3_2","title":"A Journey That Changed Everything","inst":"Write a narrative (12-15 sentences) about a journey that changed the main character.","sc":[{"l":"Opening","h":"Who is the character? Where are they going? Build the setting with descriptive language."},{"l":"Rising action","h":"What challenges or surprises happen during the journey? How does the character react?"},{"l":"Climax","h":"What is the most important or dramatic moment?"},{"l":"Resolution","h":"How does the journey end? How has the character changed?"}],"rub":"Write 12-15 sentences. Use varied sentence lengths. Include dialogue. Use descriptive language (similes, strong verbs). Show character development. Use correct punctuation throughout."},{"id":"w3_3","title":"Technology: Friend or Foe?","inst":"Write a persuasive essay (12-15 sentences) arguing your position.","sc":[{"l":"Hook and thesis","h":"Start with a compelling fact or question. State your position clearly."},{"l":"Body paragraph 1","h":"Your strongest argument with evidence or example."},{"l":"Body paragraph 2","h":"Another argument with evidence. Address a counter-argument."},{"l":"Conclusion","h":"Summarise your arguments. End with a call to action or thought-provoking statement."}],"rub":"Write 12-15 sentences. Use persuasive techniques (rhetorical questions, statistics, emotive language). Address counter-arguments. Use formal tone. Use correct punctuation throughout."}]};
const GQ={"1":[{"id":"g1_1","inst":"Calculate the perimeter of this rectangle.","shape":"rectangle_8_5","txt":"A rectangle has a length of 8cm and a width of 5cm. What is its perimeter?","opts":["13 cm","26 cm","40 cm"],"cor":1,"exp":"Perimeter = 2 x (length + width) = 2 x (8 + 5) = 2 x 13 = 26 cm"},{"id":"g1_2","inst":"Calculate the area of this rectangle.","shape":"rectangle_7_4","txt":"A rectangle has a length of 7cm and a width of 4cm. What is its area?","opts":["22 cm\u00b2","28 cm\u00b2","11 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Area = length x width = 7 x 4 = 28 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g1_3","inst":"Calculate the area of this triangle.","shape":"triangle_10_6","txt":"A triangle has a base of 10cm and a height of 6cm. What is its area?","opts":["60 cm\u00b2","30 cm\u00b2","16 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Area of triangle = (base x height) \u00f7 2 = (10 x 6) \u00f7 2 = 60 \u00f7 2 = 30 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g1_4","inst":"What type of angle is shown?","shape":"acute_angle","txt":"An angle that is less than 90 degrees is called:","opts":["Right angle","Obtuse angle","Acute angle"],"cor":2,"exp":"An acute angle is less than 90 degrees. It looks like a sharp, narrow angle."},{"id":"g1_5","inst":"What type of angle is shown?","shape":"obtuse_angle","txt":"An angle that is between 90 and 180 degrees is called:","opts":["Acute angle","Right angle","Obtuse angle"],"cor":2,"exp":"An obtuse angle is between 90\u00b0 and 180\u00b0. It is wider than a right angle."},{"id":"g1_6","inst":"Calculate the perimeter of this square.","shape":"square_9","txt":"A square has sides of 9cm. What is its perimeter?","opts":["18 cm","27 cm","36 cm"],"cor":2,"exp":"Perimeter of a square = 4 x side = 4 x 9 = 36 cm"},{"id":"g1_7","inst":"Calculate the area of this square.","shape":"square_6","txt":"A square has sides of 6cm. What is its area?","opts":["24 cm\u00b2","36 cm\u00b2","12 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Area of a square = side x side = 6 x 6 = 36 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g1_8","inst":"Look at this shape. What are these lines called?","shape":"parallel","txt":"Two lines that never meet and are always the same distance apart are called:","opts":["Perpendicular lines","Parallel lines","Diagonal lines"],"cor":1,"exp":"Parallel lines never meet and stay the same distance apart, like railway tracks."},{"id":"g1_9","inst":"Find the missing angle in this triangle.","shape":"triangle_angles","txt":"A triangle has angles of 60\u00b0 and 70\u00b0. What is the third angle?","opts":["40\u00b0","50\u00b0","60\u00b0"],"cor":1,"exp":"Angles in a triangle add up to 180\u00b0. So: 180 - 60 - 70 = 50\u00b0"},{"id":"g1_10","inst":"What is the name of this triangle?","shape":"equilateral","txt":"A triangle where all 3 sides are the same length is called:","opts":["Isosceles","Equilateral","Scalene"],"cor":1,"exp":"An equilateral triangle has all 3 sides equal. 'Equi' means equal, 'lateral' means side."},{"id":"g1_11","inst":"Calculate the volume of this cuboid.","shape":"cuboid","txt":"A cuboid is 4cm long, 3cm wide, and 2cm tall. What is its volume?","opts":["9 cm\u00b3","24 cm\u00b3","20 cm\u00b3"],"cor":1,"exp":"Volume = length x width x height = 4 x 3 x 2 = 24 cm\u00b3"},{"id":"g1_12","inst":"How many faces does a cube have?","shape":"cube","txt":"Count the faces of a cube. How many does it have?","opts":["4","6","8"],"cor":1,"exp":"A cube has 6 faces. Each face is a square."},{"id":"g1_13","inst":"What is a quadrilateral?","shape":"quadrilateral","txt":"A shape with exactly 4 sides is called a:","opts":["Triangle","Quadrilateral","Pentagon"],"cor":1,"exp":"A quadrilateral is any shape with exactly 4 sides. Quad means 4."},{"id":"g1_14","inst":"What is the perimeter of this regular hexagon?","shape":"hexagon_5","txt":"A regular hexagon has all sides equal. If one side is 5cm, what is the perimeter?","opts":["25 cm","30 cm","35 cm"],"cor":1,"exp":"A regular hexagon has 6 equal sides. Perimeter = 6 x 5 = 30 cm"},{"id":"g1_15","inst":"Identify the shape.","shape":"trapezium","txt":"A shape with exactly one pair of parallel sides is called a:","opts":["Parallelogram","Trapezium","Rhombus"],"cor":1,"exp":"A trapezium has exactly one pair of parallel sides. A parallelogram has two pairs."}],"2":[{"id":"g2_1","inst":"What is the perimeter of a rectangle with length 8cm and width 5cm?","shape":"rectangle_8_5","opts":["13 cm","26 cm","40 cm"],"cor":1,"exp":"Perimeter = 2 x (length + width) = 2 x (8 + 5) = 2 x 13 = 26 cm"},{"id":"g2_2","inst":"What is the area of a rectangle with length 7cm and width 4cm?","shape":"rectangle_7_4","opts":["22 cm\u00b2","28 cm\u00b2","11 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Area = length x width = 7 x 4 = 28 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g2_3","inst":"What is the area of a triangle with base 10cm and height 6cm?","shape":"triangle_10_6","opts":["60 cm\u00b2","30 cm\u00b2","16 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Area of triangle = (base x height) \u00f7 2 = (10 x 6) \u00f7 2 = 60 \u00f7 2 = 30 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g2_4","inst":"An angle of exactly 90 degrees is called a:","shape":"right_angle","opts":["Acute angle","Right angle","Obtuse angle"],"cor":1,"exp":"A right angle is exactly 90 degrees. It looks like the corner of a book."},{"id":"g2_5","inst":"An angle between 90 and 180 degrees is called:","shape":"obtuse_angle","opts":["Acute angle","Right angle","Obtuse angle"],"cor":2,"exp":"An obtuse angle is between 90\u00b0 and 180\u00b0. It is wider than a right angle."},{"id":"g2_6","inst":"Two lines that never meet and are always the same distance apart are called:","shape":"parallel","opts":["Perpendicular lines","Parallel lines","Diagonal lines"],"cor":1,"exp":"Parallel lines never meet and stay the same distance apart, like railway tracks."},{"id":"g2_7","inst":"What is the perimeter of a square with sides of 9cm?","shape":"square_9","opts":["18 cm","27 cm","36 cm"],"cor":2,"exp":"Perimeter of a square = 4 x side = 4 x 9 = 36 cm"},{"id":"g2_8","inst":"If a triangle has angles of 60\u00b0, 70\u00b0, what is the third angle?","shape":"triangle_angles","opts":["40\u00b0","50\u00b0","60\u00b0"],"cor":1,"exp":"Angles in a triangle add up to 180\u00b0. So: 180 - 60 - 70 = 50\u00b0"},{"id":"g2_9","inst":"What is the volume of a cuboid with length 4cm, width 3cm, and height 2cm?","shape":"cuboid","opts":["9 cm\u00b3","24 cm\u00b3","20 cm\u00b3"],"cor":1,"exp":"Volume = length x width x height = 4 x 3 x 2 = 24 cm\u00b3"},{"id":"g2_10","inst":"Two lines that cross at right angles are called:","shape":"perpendicular","opts":["Parallel lines","Perpendicular lines","Intersecting lines"],"cor":1,"exp":"Perpendicular lines meet at exactly 90 degrees (right angles)."},{"id":"g2_11","inst":"A shape has been translated 3 units to the right. This means it has:","shape":"translation","opts":["Been rotated","Slid across without changing size or shape","Been flipped over"],"cor":1,"exp":"A translation moves (slides) a shape without rotating or flipping it."},{"id":"g2_12","inst":"What is the area of a square with sides of 6cm?","shape":"square_6","opts":["24 cm\u00b2","36 cm\u00b2","12 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Area of a square = side x side = 6 x 6 = 36 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g2_13","inst":"What is a quadrilateral?","shape":"quadrilateral","opts":["A shape with 3 sides","A shape with 4 sides","A shape with 5 sides"],"cor":1,"exp":"A quadrilateral is any shape with exactly 4 sides. 'Quad' means 4."},{"id":"g2_14","inst":"What are the coordinates of a point 3 units right and 5 units up from the origin?","shape":"coordinates","opts":["(5, 3)","(3, 5)","(3, -5)"],"cor":1,"exp":"Coordinates are written as (x, y). Right = positive x, up = positive y. So (3, 5)."},{"id":"g2_15","inst":"A regular hexagon has all sides equal. If one side is 5cm, what is the perimeter?","shape":"hexagon_5","opts":["25 cm","30 cm","35 cm"],"cor":1,"exp":"A regular hexagon has 6 equal sides. Perimeter = 6 x 5 = 30 cm"}],"3":[{"id":"g3_1","inst":"What is the area of a circle with radius 7cm? (Use \u03c0 = 3.14)","shape":"circle_7","opts":["43.96 cm\u00b2","153.86 cm\u00b2","21.98 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Area = \u03c0 \u00d7 r\u00b2 = 3.14 \u00d7 7\u00b2 = 3.14 \u00d7 49 = 153.86 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g3_2","inst":"What is the circumference of a circle with diameter 10cm? (Use \u03c0 = 3.14)","shape":"circle_10","opts":["31.4 cm","62.8 cm","15.7 cm"],"cor":0,"exp":"Circumference = \u03c0 \u00d7 diameter = 3.14 \u00d7 10 = 31.4 cm"},{"id":"g3_3","inst":"The angles in a quadrilateral add up to:","shape":"quadrilateral_angles","opts":["180\u00b0","270\u00b0","360\u00b0"],"cor":2,"exp":"The interior angles of any quadrilateral always add up to 360\u00b0."},{"id":"g3_4","inst":"What is the volume of a cylinder with radius 3cm and height 10cm? (Use \u03c0 = 3.14)","shape":"cylinder_3_10","opts":["94.2 cm\u00b3","282.6 cm\u00b3","188.4 cm\u00b3"],"cor":1,"exp":"Volume = \u03c0 \u00d7 r\u00b2 \u00d7 h = 3.14 \u00d7 9 \u00d7 10 = 282.6 cm\u00b3"},{"id":"g3_5","inst":"A shape is enlarged by scale factor 2. If the original side is 5cm, what is the new side?","shape":"enlargement","opts":["7 cm","10 cm","25 cm"],"cor":1,"exp":"Scale factor 2 means each side is multiplied by 2. So 5 \u00d7 2 = 10 cm."},{"id":"g3_6","inst":"What is the area of a trapezium with parallel sides 6cm and 10cm, and height 4cm?","shape":"trapezium","opts":["24 cm\u00b2","32 cm\u00b2","40 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Area = \u00bd \u00d7 (a + b) \u00d7 h = \u00bd \u00d7 (6 + 10) \u00d7 4 = \u00bd \u00d7 16 \u00d7 4 = 32 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g3_7","inst":"In a right-angled triangle, if two short sides are 3cm and 4cm, what is the hypotenuse?","shape":"right_triangle","opts":["5 cm","6 cm","7 cm"],"cor":0,"exp":"Using Pythagoras: c\u00b2 = a\u00b2 + b\u00b2 = 9 + 16 = 25. So c = \u221a25 = 5 cm."},{"id":"g3_8","inst":"A triangle is reflected in a vertical line. What changes?","shape":"reflection","opts":["Its size","Its left-right orientation","Its angles"],"cor":1,"exp":"A reflection flips the shape, reversing its left-right orientation. Size and angles stay the same."},{"id":"g3_9","inst":"What is the surface area of a cube with sides of 4cm?","shape":"cube_4","opts":["64 cm\u00b2","96 cm\u00b2","48 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Surface area = 6 \u00d7 side\u00b2 = 6 \u00d7 16 = 96 cm\u00b2. A cube has 6 faces, each is 4\u00d74=16."},{"id":"g3_10","inst":"An exterior angle of a regular polygon is 45\u00b0. How many sides does it have?","shape":"polygon","opts":["6","8","10"],"cor":1,"exp":"Exterior angles of a regular polygon add up to 360\u00b0. Number of sides = 360 \u00f7 45 = 8."},{"id":"g3_11","inst":"What is the area of a parallelogram with base 12cm and perpendicular height 5cm?","shape":"parallelogram","opts":["17 cm\u00b2","34 cm\u00b2","60 cm\u00b2"],"cor":2,"exp":"Area of parallelogram = base \u00d7 perpendicular height = 12 \u00d7 5 = 60 cm\u00b2"},{"id":"g3_12","inst":"A shape is rotated 90\u00b0 clockwise about the origin. Point (2, 3) becomes:","shape":"rotation","opts":["(3, -2)","(-3, 2)","(-2, -3)"],"cor":0,"exp":"For a 90\u00b0 clockwise rotation about the origin: (x, y) becomes (y, -x). So (2, 3) becomes (3, -2)."},{"id":"g3_13","inst":"Two similar triangles have a scale factor of 3. If the area of the small triangle is 5cm\u00b2, what is the area of the large one?","shape":"similar","opts":["15 cm\u00b2","45 cm\u00b2","125 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"For similar shapes, area scale factor = (linear scale factor)\u00b2. Area = 5 \u00d7 3\u00b2 = 5 \u00d7 9 = 45 cm\u00b2."},{"id":"g3_14","inst":"What is the volume of a triangular prism with cross-section area 12cm\u00b2 and length 8cm?","shape":"prism","opts":["20 cm\u00b3","48 cm\u00b3","96 cm\u00b3"],"cor":2,"exp":"Volume of prism = cross-section area \u00d7 length = 12 \u00d7 8 = 96 cm\u00b3."},{"id":"g3_15","inst":"Bearings are measured clockwise from North. What bearing is due East?","shape":"bearing","opts":["090\u00b0","180\u00b0","270\u00b0"],"cor":0,"exp":"East is 90\u00b0 clockwise from North. Bearings always use 3 digits, so it's 090\u00b0."}],"4":[{"id":"g4_1","inst":"Calculate the area of the shaded region.","shape":"circle_7","txt":"A circle has radius 7cm. A square of side 8cm is cut from inside it. What is the area of the remaining circular region? (Use \u03c0 = 3.14)","opts":["89.86 cm\u00b2","153.86 cm\u00b2","217.86 cm\u00b2"],"cor":0,"exp":"Circle area = 3.14 \u00d7 49 = 153.86 cm\u00b2. Square area = 64 cm\u00b2. Remaining = 153.86 - 64 = 89.86 cm\u00b2."},{"id":"g4_2","inst":"Use trigonometry.","shape":"right_triangle","txt":"In a right-angled triangle, one angle is 35\u00b0 and the hypotenuse is 10cm. What is the length of the opposite side? (sin 35\u00b0 = 0.574)","opts":["5.74 cm","8.19 cm","3.57 cm"],"cor":0,"exp":"sin(35\u00b0) = opposite/hypotenuse. Opposite = 10 \u00d7 sin(35\u00b0) = 10 \u00d7 0.574 = 5.74 cm."},{"id":"g4_3","inst":"Calculate.","shape":"cylinder_3_10","txt":"A cone has the same radius (3cm) and height (10cm) as a cylinder. What fraction of the cylinder\u2019s volume is the cone? Express as a simplified fraction.","opts":["1/3","1/2","2/3"],"cor":0,"exp":"Volume of cone = 1/3 \u00d7 \u03c0r\u00b2h. Volume of cylinder = \u03c0r\u00b2h. Fraction = 1/3."},{"id":"g4_4","inst":"Find the angle.","shape":"triangle_angles","txt":"An isosceles triangle has one angle of 40\u00b0 at the top. What are the two base angles?","opts":["70\u00b0 each","80\u00b0 each","60\u00b0 each"],"cor":0,"exp":"Sum = 180\u00b0. Base angles = (180 - 40) \u00f7 2 = 140 \u00f7 2 = 70\u00b0 each."},{"id":"g4_5","inst":"Calculate the surface area.","shape":"cylinder_3_10","txt":"A cylinder has radius 3cm and height 10cm. Calculate its total surface area. (\u03c0 = 3.14)","opts":["188.4 cm\u00b2","245.04 cm\u00b2","282.6 cm\u00b2"],"cor":1,"exp":"SA = 2\u03c0r\u00b2 + 2\u03c0rh = 2(3.14)(9) + 2(3.14)(3)(10) = 56.52 + 188.4 = 244.92 \u2248 245.04 cm\u00b2."}],"5":[{"id":"g5_1","inst":"Vector geometry.","shape":"parallelogram","txt":"In parallelogram ABCD, vector AB = (3,4) and vector AD = (5,0). Find the magnitude of diagonal AC.","opts":["\u221a89","\u221a80","\u221a73"],"cor":2,"exp":"AC = AB + AD = (3+5, 4+0) = (8,4). |AC| = \u221a(64+16) = \u221a80. Wait \u2014 let me recalculate: (8,4), |AC|=\u221a(64+16)=\u221a80=4\u221a5."},{"id":"g5_2","inst":"Circle theorem.","shape":"circle_7","txt":"Two chords intersect inside a circle. One chord is split into segments of 3cm and 8cm. The other chord has one segment of 4cm. What is its other segment?","opts":["6 cm","5 cm","7 cm"],"cor":0,"exp":"Intersecting chords theorem: 3 \u00d7 8 = 4 \u00d7 x. 24 = 4x. x = 6 cm."},{"id":"g5_3","inst":"Advanced area.","shape":"trapezium","txt":"A trapezium has parallel sides 6cm and 10cm, height 4cm, and one non-parallel side of 5cm. Calculate the area. Then find the perimeter given the other non-parallel side is 4.5cm.","opts":["A=32cm\u00b2, P=25.5cm","A=40cm\u00b2, P=25.5cm","A=32cm\u00b2, P=24cm"],"cor":0,"exp":"Area = \u00bd(6+10)\u00d74 = 32 cm\u00b2. Perimeter = 6+10+5+4.5 = 25.5 cm."}]};
const PS={"1":[{"id":"ps1_1","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A bakery makes 156 cupcakes on Monday and 248 on Tuesday. They pack them into boxes of 12. How many full boxes can they make?","opts":["32","33","34"],"cor":2,"exp":"156 + 248 = 404 cupcakes. 404 ÷ 12 = 33 remainder 8. So 33 full boxes. Wait — let's recheck: 33×12=396, 34×12=408. So 33 full boxes with 8 left over. Answer: 33."},{"id":"ps1_2","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A school trip costs £8.50 per child. There are 28 children going. The school has a budget of £250. How much more money do they need?","opts":["£12","£8","£38"],"cor":1,"exp":"28 × £8.50 = £238. They need £238 - £250... wait, £238 < £250, so they have enough! Actually 28 × 8.50: 28×8=224, 28×0.50=14, total=238. 250-238=12. They have £12 spare. But the question asks how much MORE they need — they don't need more, they have £12 left."},{"id":"ps1_3","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"Mia runs 1.5 km each day from Monday to Friday, and 3.2 km on Saturday. She rests on Sunday. How far does she run in one week?","opts":["10.7 km","9.5 km","11.2 km"],"cor":0,"exp":"Monday to Friday = 5 days × 1.5 km = 7.5 km. Saturday = 3.2 km. Total = 7.5 + 3.2 = 10.7 km."},{"id":"ps1_4","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A swimming pool is 25 metres long. Tom swims 14 lengths in the morning and 8 lengths in the afternoon. How many metres does he swim in total?","opts":["450 m","500 m","550 m"],"cor":2,"exp":"14 + 8 = 22 lengths. 22 × 25 = 550 metres."},{"id":"ps1_5","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A fruit stall sells apples at £1.20 per kg and oranges at £1.85 per kg. Sarah buys 2.5 kg of apples and 1 kg of oranges. How much does she spend?","opts":["£4.85","£4.50","£5.85"],"cor":0,"exp":"Apples: 2.5 × £1.20 = £3.00. Oranges: 1 × £1.85 = £1.85. Total: £3.00 + £1.85 = £4.85."},{"id":"ps1_6","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A recipe for 6 people needs 450g of pasta. How much pasta is needed for 10 people?","opts":["700g","750g","800g"],"cor":1,"exp":"Per person: 450 ÷ 6 = 75g. For 10 people: 75 × 10 = 750g."},{"id":"ps1_7","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A train leaves at 09:47 and the journey takes 1 hour 38 minutes. What time does it arrive?","opts":["11:15","11:25","11:35"],"cor":1,"exp":"09:47 + 1 hour = 10:47. 10:47 + 38 minutes: 10:47 + 13min = 11:00, then +25min = 11:25."},{"id":"ps1_8","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A car park charges £2.40 for the first hour and £1.50 for each extra hour. How much does it cost to park for 4 hours?","opts":["£6.00","£6.90","£8.40"],"cor":1,"exp":"First hour: £2.40. Extra 3 hours: 3 × £1.50 = £4.50. Total: £2.40 + £4.50 = £6.90."},{"id":"ps1_9","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"In a class of 32 children, 3/8 chose football as their favourite sport. How many children chose football?","opts":["8","12","16"],"cor":1,"exp":"3/8 of 32 = 32 ÷ 8 × 3 = 4 × 3 = 12 children."},{"id":"ps1_10","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A rectangular garden is 12.5 m long and 8 m wide. What is its perimeter?","opts":["41 m","100 m","20.5 m"],"cor":0,"exp":"Perimeter = 2 × (length + width) = 2 × (12.5 + 8) = 2 × 20.5 = 41 m."},{"id":"ps1_11","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"Sam has £20. He buys 3 notebooks at £2.75 each and a pen for £1.50. How much change does he get?","opts":["£10.25","£10.50","£12.25"],"cor":0,"exp":"Notebooks: 3 × £2.75 = £8.25. Pen: £1.50. Total spent: £8.25 + £1.50 = £9.75. Change: £20 - £9.75 = £10.25."},{"id":"ps1_12","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A water tank holds 240 litres. It is 5/8 full. How many more litres are needed to fill it?","opts":["90 litres","150 litres","100 litres"],"cor":0,"exp":"5/8 full = 5/8 × 240 = 150 litres in tank. Empty = 240 - 150 = 90 litres needed."},{"id":"ps1_13","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"The temperature at 6am was -4°C. By noon it had risen by 11 degrees. What was the temperature at noon?","opts":["7°C","15°C","-15°C"],"cor":0,"exp":"-4 + 11 = 7°C."},{"id":"ps1_14","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A bag of sweets weighs 350g. How many bags can be filled from 5 kg of sweets?","opts":["12","14","15"],"cor":1,"exp":"5 kg = 5000g. 5000 ÷ 350 = 14.28... So 14 full bags (we can't have a partial bag)."},{"id":"ps1_15","inst":"Solve this word problem.","txt":"A shop gives 20% discount. A jacket costs £45. What is the sale price?","opts":["£36","£38","£40"],"cor":0,"exp":"20% of £45 = £9. Sale price = £45 - £9 = £36."}],"2":[{"id":"ps2_1","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A shop sells pencils for 35p each. How much do 8 pencils cost?","opts":["\u00a32.40","\u00a32.80","\u00a33.15"],"cor":1,"exp":"35 \u00d7 8 = 280p = \u00a32.80"},{"id":"ps2_2","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A rectangle has a perimeter of 36cm. If the length is 12cm, what is the width?","opts":["6 cm","8 cm","12 cm"],"cor":0,"exp":"Perimeter = 2(l+w). 36 = 2(12+w). 18 = 12+w. w = 6cm."},{"id":"ps2_3","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"Train A leaves at 09:45 and arrives at 11:20. How long is the journey?","opts":["1 hour 25 minutes","1 hour 35 minutes","1 hour 45 minutes"],"cor":1,"exp":"09:45 to 10:45 = 1 hour. 10:45 to 11:20 = 35 min. Total = 1hr 35min."},{"id":"ps2_4","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A bag has 3 red balls, 5 blue balls, and 2 green balls. What fraction of the balls are blue?","opts":["3/10","5/10","2/10"],"cor":1,"exp":"Total = 3+5+2 = 10. Blue = 5. Fraction = 5/10 = 1/2."},{"id":"ps2_5","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A school has 240 students. 3/8 of them walk to school. How many students walk?","opts":["80","90","120"],"cor":1,"exp":"240 \u00d7 3/8 = 240 \u00f7 8 \u00d7 3 = 30 \u00d7 3 = 90 students."},{"id":"ps2_6","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"Books cost \u00a34.50 each. With \u00a320, what is the most books you can buy?","opts":["3","4","5"],"cor":1,"exp":"\u00a320 \u00f7 \u00a34.50 = 4.44... So you can buy 4 books (\u00a318). Not enough for 5 (\u00a322.50)."},{"id":"ps2_7","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A car travels at 60 km/h. How far does it travel in 2.5 hours?","opts":["120 km","150 km","180 km"],"cor":1,"exp":"Distance = speed \u00d7 time = 60 \u00d7 2.5 = 150 km."},{"id":"ps2_8","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"The temperature was -3\u00b0C in the morning and rose by 8 degrees. What is the temperature now?","opts":["5\u00b0C","11\u00b0C","-11\u00b0C"],"cor":0,"exp":"-3 + 8 = 5\u00b0C. Starting below zero and adding 8."},{"id":"ps2_9","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A recipe for 4 people needs 300g of flour. How much flour is needed for 6 people?","opts":["400g","450g","500g"],"cor":1,"exp":"300 \u00f7 4 = 75g per person. 75 \u00d7 6 = 450g."},{"id":"ps2_10","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"What is 15% of 80?","opts":["10","12","15"],"cor":1,"exp":"10% of 80 = 8. 5% of 80 = 4. So 15% = 8 + 4 = 12."},{"id":"ps2_11","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A box is 30cm long, 20cm wide, and 10cm tall. What is its volume?","opts":["600 cm\u00b3","6000 cm\u00b3","60 cm\u00b3"],"cor":1,"exp":"Volume = 30 \u00d7 20 \u00d7 10 = 6000 cm\u00b3."},{"id":"ps2_12","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"Sam scores 72, 85, 68, and 91 in four tests. What is his mean score?","opts":["76","79","82"],"cor":1,"exp":"Mean = (72+85+68+91) \u00f7 4 = 316 \u00f7 4 = 79."},{"id":"ps2_13","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A shirt is \u00a340. It is reduced by 25% in a sale. What is the sale price?","opts":["\u00a325","\u00a330","\u00a335"],"cor":1,"exp":"25% of \u00a340 = \u00a310. Sale price = \u00a340 - \u00a310 = \u00a330."},{"id":"ps2_14","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"3/4 of a number is 36. What is the number?","opts":["27","48","52"],"cor":1,"exp":"If 3/4 = 36, then 1/4 = 12. The whole number = 4 \u00d7 12 = 48."},{"id":"ps2_15","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"The ratio of cats to dogs in a shelter is 3:5. If there are 24 animals, how many are dogs?","opts":["9","12","15"],"cor":2,"exp":"3+5=8 parts. Each part = 24\u00f78 = 3. Dogs = 5\u00d73 = 15."}],"3":[{"id":"ps3_1","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A phone costs \u00a3480. It is reduced by 15%, then a further 10% off the reduced price. What is the final price?","opts":["\u00a3360.00","\u00a3367.20","\u00a3372.00"],"cor":1,"exp":"15% off: \u00a3480 \u00d7 0.85 = \u00a3408. Then 10% off: \u00a3408 \u00d7 0.90 = \u00a3367.20."},{"id":"ps3_2","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A car depreciates by 20% each year. It was bought for \u00a315,000. What is it worth after 2 years?","opts":["\u00a39,000","\u00a39,600","\u00a310,800"],"cor":1,"exp":"After 1yr: \u00a315000 \u00d7 0.8 = \u00a312000. After 2yr: \u00a312000 \u00d7 0.8 = \u00a39600."},{"id":"ps3_3","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"Solve: 3x + 7 = 22. What is x?","opts":["3","5","7"],"cor":1,"exp":"3x + 7 = 22. 3x = 15. x = 5."},{"id":"ps3_4","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A map has a scale of 1:50,000. Two towns are 8cm apart on the map. What is the real distance in km?","opts":["4 km","40 km","400 km"],"cor":0,"exp":"8cm \u00d7 50000 = 400000cm = 4000m = 4km."},{"id":"ps3_5","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"The probability of picking a red sweet is 0.3. Out of 200 sweets, how many would you expect to be red?","opts":["30","60","90"],"cor":1,"exp":"Expected = probability \u00d7 total = 0.3 \u00d7 200 = 60."},{"id":"ps3_6","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A cylinder has radius 5cm and height 12cm. What is its volume? (\u03c0 = 3.14)","opts":["188.4 cm\u00b3","628 cm\u00b3","942 cm\u00b3"],"cor":2,"exp":"V = \u03c0r\u00b2h = 3.14 \u00d7 25 \u00d7 12 = 942 cm\u00b3."},{"id":"ps3_7","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"\u00a3500 is invested at 4% simple interest per year. How much interest is earned in 3 years?","opts":["\u00a320","\u00a340","\u00a360"],"cor":2,"exp":"Simple interest = 500 \u00d7 0.04 \u00d7 3 = \u00a360."},{"id":"ps3_8","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"The nth term of a sequence is 3n + 2. What is the 10th term?","opts":["30","32","35"],"cor":1,"exp":"Substitute n=10: 3(10)+2 = 30+2 = 32."},{"id":"ps3_9","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A triangle has sides 5cm, 12cm, and 13cm. Is it a right-angled triangle?","opts":["Yes","No","Cannot tell"],"cor":0,"exp":"Check: 5\u00b2 + 12\u00b2 = 25 + 144 = 169 = 13\u00b2. Since a\u00b2+b\u00b2=c\u00b2, yes, it is right-angled."},{"id":"ps3_10","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"Expand and simplify: 2(3x + 4) + 3(x - 2)","opts":["9x + 2","9x + 14","6x + 2"],"cor":0,"exp":"2(3x+4) = 6x+8. 3(x-2) = 3x-6. Combined: 6x+3x+8-6 = 9x+2."},{"id":"ps3_11","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A bag has 4 red and 6 blue balls. Two balls are picked without replacement. What is the probability both are red?","opts":["2/15","4/25","4/30"],"cor":0,"exp":"P(1st red) = 4/10. P(2nd red) = 3/9. P(both) = 4/10 \u00d7 3/9 = 12/90 = 2/15."},{"id":"ps3_12","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"If y = x\u00b2 - 4x + 3, what are the values of x when y = 0?","opts":["x=1 and x=3","x=2 and x=3","x=-1 and x=-3"],"cor":0,"exp":"x\u00b2-4x+3=0. Factorise: (x-1)(x-3)=0. So x=1 or x=3."},{"id":"ps3_13","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A shape is enlarged by scale factor 3. Its original area was 8cm\u00b2. What is the new area?","opts":["24 cm\u00b2","48 cm\u00b2","72 cm\u00b2"],"cor":2,"exp":"Area scale factor = 3\u00b2 = 9. New area = 8 \u00d7 9 = 72 cm\u00b2."},{"id":"ps3_14","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"The mean of five numbers is 12. Four of the numbers are 10, 14, 8, and 15. What is the fifth number?","opts":["11","13","15"],"cor":1,"exp":"Total = 5 \u00d7 12 = 60. Sum of four = 47. Fifth = 60-47 = 13."},{"id":"ps3_15","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A boat sails 12km East then 9km North. How far is it from the start? (straight line)","opts":["15 km","21 km","10.5 km"],"cor":0,"exp":"Using Pythagoras: d\u00b2 = 12\u00b2 + 9\u00b2 = 144+81 = 225. d = \u221a225 = 15 km."}],"4":[{"id":"ps4_1","inst":"Solve this multi-step problem.","txt":"A shop buys 200 t-shirts at \u00a35.50 each and sells 75% of them at \u00a312 each, and the rest at \u00a38 each (sale price). Calculate the total profit.","opts":["\u00a3500","\u00a3700","\u00a3600"],"cor":0,"exp":"Cost: 200\u00d7\u00a35.50=\u00a31100. Sold at \u00a312: 150\u00d7\u00a312=\u00a31800. Sold at \u00a38: 50\u00d7\u00a38=\u00a3400. Revenue=\u00a32200. Profit=\u00a32200-\u00a31100=\u00a31100. Hmm, let me recheck... 200\u00d75.50=1100. 150\u00d712=1800. 50\u00d78=400. Total=2200. Profit=2200-1100=1100."},{"id":"ps4_2","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"Two trains leave the same station at the same time. Train A goes north at 90 km/h. Train B goes east at 120 km/h. How far apart are they after 2 hours?","opts":["300 km","420 km","150 km"],"cor":0,"exp":"After 2h: A=180km north, B=240km east. Distance = \u221a(180\u00b2+240\u00b2) = \u221a(32400+57600) = \u221a90000 = 300 km."},{"id":"ps4_3","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"Solve simultaneously: 2x + 3y = 16 and 4x - y = 10","opts":["x=3.29, y=3.14","x=3, y=2","x=4, y=6"],"cor":0,"exp":"From eq2: y=4x-10. Sub into eq1: 2x+3(4x-10)=16. 2x+12x-30=16. 14x=46. x=46/14=23/7\u22483.29. y=4(23/7)-10=92/7-70/7=22/7\u22483.14."}],"5":[{"id":"ps5_1","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"A ball is thrown upward with height h = 20t - 5t\u00b2 metres after t seconds. (a) When does it reach maximum height? (b) What is the maximum height? (c) When does it hit the ground?","opts":["t=2s, h=20m, ground at t=4s","t=2s, h=15m, ground at t=4s","t=4s, h=20m, ground at t=8s"],"cor":0,"exp":"Max at t = -20/(2\u00d7-5) = 2s. h(2) = 40-20 = 20m. Ground: 20t-5t\u00b2=0, t(20-5t)=0, t=0 or t=4s."},{"id":"ps5_2","inst":"Solve this problem.","txt":"\u00a33000 is invested at 4.5% compound interest. After how many complete years will the investment first exceed \u00a33500?","opts":["3 years","4 years","5 years"],"cor":1,"exp":"Y1: 3000\u00d71.045=3135. Y2: 3135\u00d71.045=3276.08. Y3: 3276.08\u00d71.045=3423.50. Y4: 3423.50\u00d71.045=3577.56>3500. Answer: 4 years."}]};
const NQ={"1":[{"id":"n1_1","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is 3/4 + 2/5?","opts":["5/9","23/20","1/2"],"cor":1,"exp":"Common denominator 20: 15/20 + 8/20 = 23/20 = 1 and 3/20."},{"id":"n1_2","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is 15% of 240?","opts":["36","42","48"],"cor":0,"exp":"10% of 240 = 24. 5% = 12. So 15% = 24 + 12 = 36."},{"id":"n1_3","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is 2.4 × 3.5?","opts":["7.2","8.4","8.0"],"cor":1,"exp":"24 × 35 = 840. Two decimal places: 8.40 = 8.4."},{"id":"n1_4","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"Simplify the fraction 36/48.","opts":["3/4","2/3","4/6"],"cor":0,"exp":"GCD of 36 and 48 is 12. 36÷12=3, 48÷12=4. Answer: 3/4."},{"id":"n1_5","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is (-7) + 12?","opts":["5","-5","19"],"cor":0,"exp":"Start at -7, move 12 to the right on the number line: -7 + 12 = 5."},{"id":"n1_6","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is 7² - 3²?","opts":["40","16","58"],"cor":0,"exp":"7² = 49. 3² = 9. 49 - 9 = 40."},{"id":"n1_7","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"Convert 0.65 to a fraction in simplest form.","opts":["65/100","13/20","6/10"],"cor":1,"exp":"0.65 = 65/100. Divide both by 5: 13/20."},{"id":"n1_8","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is 5/6 of 72?","opts":["60","65","54"],"cor":0,"exp":"72 ÷ 6 = 12. 12 × 5 = 60."},{"id":"n1_9","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"Arrange from smallest to largest: 0.7, 3/4, 68%","opts":["68%, 0.7, 3/4","0.7, 68%, 3/4","3/4, 0.7, 68%"],"cor":0,"exp":"68% = 0.68, 0.7 = 0.70, 3/4 = 0.75. Order: 0.68, 0.70, 0.75."},{"id":"n1_10","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is √81?","opts":["8","9","27"],"cor":1,"exp":"9 × 9 = 81, so √81 = 9."},{"id":"n1_11","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is 4.8 ÷ 0.6?","opts":["8","6","0.8"],"cor":0,"exp":"48 ÷ 6 = 8. (Move decimal in both: 48÷6=8.)"},{"id":"n1_12","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"What is 2/3 × 4/5?","opts":["8/15","6/8","6/15"],"cor":0,"exp":"2/3 × 4/5 = (2×4)/(3×5) = 8/15."},{"id":"n1_13","inst":"Calculate.","txt":"Increase £60 by 15%.","opts":["£69","£75","£66"],"cor":0,"exp":"15% of 60 = 9. £60 +