  science_biology:{"1":[
    {"id":"sbio1_1","q":"Explain the differences between a plant cell and an animal cell. Name at least 3 structures that are different and explain what each one does.","hint":"Think about: cell wall, chloroplasts, vacuole. What does each do?","answer":"Plant cells have: 1) Cell wall (made of cellulose, provides rigid support and shape), 2) Chloroplasts (contain chlorophyll for photosynthesis - making food from sunlight), 3) Large permanent vacuole (filled with cell sap, keeps the cell turgid/firm). Animal cells do not have any of these three structures.","marks":4},
    {"id":"sbio1_2","q":"Draw and label a simple food chain with 4 organisms. For each organism, state whether it is a producer, primary consumer, secondary consumer, or tertiary consumer. Explain why energy decreases at each level.","hint":"Start with a plant. Remember energy is lost as heat through respiration at each level.","answer":"Example: Grass (producer) -> Rabbit (primary consumer) -> Fox (secondary consumer) -> Eagle (tertiary consumer). Energy decreases because at each level organisms use energy for movement, growth, and body heat through respiration. Only about 10% of energy passes to the next level.","marks":5}
  ],"2":[
    {"id":"sbio2_1","q":"Explain how the structure of the small intestine is adapted for absorbing nutrients. Describe at least 3 adaptations.","hint":"Think about surface area, blood supply, and wall thickness.","answer":"1) Villi (finger-like projections) increase the surface area for absorption. 2) Very thin walls (one cell thick) so nutrients can pass through quickly by diffusion. 3) Rich blood supply (capillary network) maintains a concentration gradient to absorb nutrients efficiently. 4) Very long (about 6m) providing maximum absorption time.","marks":4}
  ]},
  science_chemistry:{"1":[
    {"id":"schem1_1","q":"A student heats ice from -10 degrees C to 120 degrees C. Describe the changes of state that happen and name each process. At what temperatures do the changes happen?","hint":"Ice melts at 0 degrees C, water boils at 100 degrees C. Name each state change.","answer":"Starting as ice (solid), it is heated. At 0 degrees C it melts (melting) turning from solid to liquid water. The water continues to heat up. At 100 degrees C it boils (boiling/evaporation), turning from liquid to gas (steam/water vapour). So two changes of state: melting at 0 degrees C and boiling at 100 degrees C.","marks":4},
    {"id":"schem1_2","q":"Describe how you would separate a mixture of sand, salt, and water using laboratory equipment. Explain each step.","hint":"Think about which separation technique works for each substance: filtration, evaporation.","answer":"Step 1: Filter the mixture through filter paper in a funnel. The sand stays on the filter paper (residue) because its particles are too big to pass through. Step 2: The salt solution (filtrate) passes through. Step 3: Heat the salt solution in an evaporating dish. The water evaporates, leaving solid salt crystals behind.","marks":4}
  ],"2":[
    {"id":"schem2_1","q":"Magnesium reacts with hydrochloric acid. Write the word equation. Describe what you would observe during the reaction and explain how you know a chemical change has occurred.","hint":"Metal + acid -> salt + hydrogen. Think about bubbles, temperature, and the magnesium dissolving.","answer":"Word equation: Magnesium + Hydrochloric acid -> Magnesium chloride + Hydrogen. Observations: bubbles/fizzing (hydrogen gas produced), magnesium ribbon dissolves/gets smaller, test tube feels warm (exothermic reaction), solution remains colourless. It is a chemical change because new substances are formed that cannot easily be changed back.","marks":5}
  ]},
  science_physics:{"1":[
    {"id":"sphys1_1","q":"A car has a mass of 1200 kg and is travelling at a constant speed of 30 m/s. Explain what the forces acting on the car must be like for it to maintain constant speed. What would happen if the driving force increased?","hint":"Think about balanced and unbalanced forces. Constant speed means no acceleration.","answer":"For constant speed, the forces must be balanced - the driving force (engine pushing forward) equals the resistive forces (friction and air resistance pushing backward). If the driving force increased, the forces would become unbalanced. There would be a resultant forward force, causing the car to accelerate (speed up) according to Newton's Second Law (F=ma).","marks":4},
    {"id":"sphys1_2","q":"Explain the difference between a series circuit and a parallel circuit. What happens to the brightness of bulbs in each type when you add more bulbs?","hint":"Think about paths for current, and how voltage is shared.","answer":"Series: one path for current, all components in a single loop. Adding more bulbs makes each dimmer because the voltage is shared between more bulbs and resistance increases. Parallel: multiple paths for current, each bulb on its own branch. Adding more bulbs does not affect brightness because each gets the full battery voltage.","marks":4}
  ],"2":[
    {"id":"sphys2_1","q":"A kettle uses 2000W of power. It takes 3 minutes to boil water. Calculate the energy transferred in joules and in kilowatt-hours. Show your working.","hint":"Energy = Power x Time. Convert minutes to seconds for joules. For kWh, convert W to kW and minutes to hours.","answer":"In joules: Time = 3 x 60 = 180 seconds. Energy = 2000W x 180s = 360,000 J (360 kJ). In kWh: Power = 2kW. Time = 3/60 = 0.05 hours. Energy = 2 x 0.05 = 0.1 kWh.","marks":4}
  ]},
  science_earthSpace:{"1":[
    {"id":"searth1_1","q":"Describe the three types of rock in the rock cycle (igneous, sedimentary, metamorphic). For each type, explain how it is formed and give one example.","hint":"Think about: cooling magma, layers of sediment being compressed, and heat/pressure changing existing rock.","answer":"1) Igneous: formed when magma/lava cools and solidifies. Example: granite (slow cooling underground = large crystals) or basalt (fast cooling on surface = small crystals). 2) Sedimentary: formed when layers of sediment are deposited and compressed over millions of years. Example: sandstone or limestone. 3) Metamorphic: formed when existing rock is changed by extreme heat and pressure (without melting). Example: marble (from limestone) or slate (from mudstone).","marks":5},
    {"id":"searth1_2","q":"Explain why we have seasons (summer and winter) on Earth. Why is it warmer in summer?","hint":"Think about the tilt of Earth's axis and how it affects sunlight angle and day length.","answer":"Earth's axis is tilted at 23.5 degrees. In summer, our hemisphere tilts towards the Sun so: 1) sunlight hits the surface more directly (concentrated energy), 2) days are longer giving more hours of heating. In winter, our hemisphere tilts away so sunlight hits at a shallow angle (spread out, less intense) and days are shorter.","marks":4}
  ],"2":[
    {"id":"searth2_1","q":"Explain how burning fossil fuels contributes to climate change. Include the greenhouse effect in your answer.","hint":"Think about CO2, the greenhouse effect, and how temperature rises.","answer":"Burning fossil fuels (coal, oil, gas) releases CO2 that was stored millions of years ago. This increases the concentration of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere. The greenhouse effect: sunlight passes through the atmosphere and warms the Earth. The Earth emits infrared radiation (heat) back up, but greenhouse gases (CO2, methane) trap this heat instead of letting it escape to space. More greenhouse gases = more heat trapped = global temperatures rise = climate change.","marks":5}
