{"id":"phys1_9","inst":"Think about light.","txt":"Light travels in:","opts":["Curved lines","Straight lines","Zigzag patterns"],"cor":1,"exp":"Light travels in straight lines (we call these rays). This is why shadows form - light cannot bend around opaque objects."},
{"id":"phys1_10","inst":"Think about electricity.","txt":"Which of these materials is an electrical conductor?","opts":["Rubber","Wood","Copper"],"cor":2,"exp":"Copper is a metal and an excellent electrical conductor because it has free electrons that can carry electric current. Rubber and wood are insulators."},
{"id":"phys1_11","inst":"Think about magnets.","shape":"magnet","txt":"What happens when you bring two north poles of magnets together?","opts":["They attract","They repel","Nothing happens"],"cor":1,"exp":"Like poles repel (N-N or S-S push apart). Unlike poles attract (N-S pull together). This is the fundamental rule of magnetism."},
{"id":"phys1_12","inst":"Think about gravity.","txt":"What is the approximate gravitational field strength on Earth?","opts":["5 N/kg","10 N/kg","15 N/kg"],"cor":1,"exp":"On Earth, g is approximately 10 N/kg (more precisely 9.8). This means a 1 kg mass has a weight of about 10 Newtons. Weight = mass x gravitational field strength."}
],"2":[
{"id":"phys2_1","inst":"Think about speed.","txt":"A car travels 120 km in 2 hours. What is its average speed?","opts":["60 km/h","120 km/h","240 km/h"],"cor":0,"exp":"Speed = distance / time = 120 km / 2 hours = 60 km/h. This is the average speed - the car may have gone faster or slower at different points."},
{"id":"phys2_2","inst":"Think about pressure.","txt":"A box weighs 600 N and sits on a base area of 2 m squared. What is the pressure it exerts?","opts":["300 Pa","600 Pa","1200 Pa"],"cor":0,"exp":"Pressure = Force / Area = 600 N / 2 m2 = 300 Pa (Pascals). Smaller area = more pressure (this is why sharp knives cut better than blunt ones)."},
{"id":"phys2_3","inst":"Think about work and energy.","txt":"A force of 50 N moves an object 4 metres. How much work is done?","opts":["12.5 J","54 J","200 J"],"cor":2,"exp":"Work = Force x Distance = 50 N x 4 m = 200 Joules. Work is the energy transferred when a force moves an object."},
{"id":"phys2_4","inst":"Think about electricity.","shape":"circuit_series","txt":"A circuit has a voltage of 12V and a current of 3A. What is the resistance?","opts":["4 ohms","36 ohms","15 ohms"],"cor":0,"exp":"Using Ohm's Law: V = I x R, so R = V / I = 12V / 3A = 4 ohms. Resistance is how much a component opposes the flow of current."},
{"id":"phys2_5","inst":"Think about waves.","shape":"wave","txt":"A wave has a frequency of 5 Hz and a wavelength of 3m. What is its speed?","opts":["1.67 m/s","8 m/s","15 m/s"],"cor":2,"exp":"Wave speed = frequency x wavelength = 5 Hz x 3 m = 15 m/s. Frequency means 5 complete waves pass a point every second."},
{"id":"phys2_6","inst":"Think about density.","txt":"An object has a mass of 500g and a volume of 250 cm cubed. What is its density?","opts":["0.5 g/cm3","2 g/cm3","750 g/cm3"],"cor":1,"exp":"Density = mass / volume = 500g / 250 cm3 = 2 g/cm3. Since water has a density of 1 g/cm3, this object would sink."},
{"id":"phys2_7","inst":"Think about forces.","txt":"A 70 kg person stands on Earth (g = 10 N/kg). What is their weight?","opts":["7 N","70 N","700 N"],"cor":2,"exp":"Weight = mass x gravitational field strength = 70 kg x 10 N/kg = 700 N. Weight is a force (measured in Newtons), mass is an amount of matter (measured in kg)."},
{"id":"phys2_8","inst":"Think about efficiency.","txt":"A light bulb uses 100J of energy but only 25J becomes light. What is its efficiency?","opts":["25%","50%","75%"],"cor":0,"exp":"Efficiency = useful energy output / total energy input x 100 = 25/100 x 100 = 25%. The other 75J is wasted as heat."}
],"3":[
{"id":"phys3_1","inst":"Think about motion.","txt":"A car accelerates from 0 to 20 m/s in 5 seconds. What is its acceleration?","opts":["4 m/s2","25 m/s2","100 m/s2"],"cor":0,"exp":"Acceleration = change in velocity / time = (20 - 0) / 5 = 4 m/s2. This means the car gets 4 m/s faster every second."},
{"id":"phys3_2","inst":"Think about Newton's laws.","txt":"A 5 kg object is pushed with a force of 20 N. What is its acceleration? (F = ma)","opts":["4 m/s2","100 m/s2","25 m/s2"],"cor":0,"exp":"F = ma, so a = F/m = 20N / 5kg = 4 m/s2. Newton's Second Law: the acceleration of an object is proportional to the force and inversely proportional to its mass."},
{"id":"phys3_3","inst":"Think about electromagnetism.","txt":"How can you increase the strength of an electromagnet?","opts":["Use fewer coils","Increase the current","Use a wooden core"],"cor":1,"exp":"Increasing the current makes the magnetic field stronger. You can also: add more coils of wire, or use an iron core (instead of wood or air)."},
{"id":"phys3_4","inst":"Think about energy.","txt":"A 2 kg ball is lifted 5m high (g = 10 N/kg). What gravitational potential energy does it gain?","opts":["10 J","50 J","100 J"],"cor":2,"exp":"GPE = mass x g x height = 2 x 10 x 5 = 100 J. This energy is stored due to the ball's position in the gravitational field."}
]};
const SCI_EARTH={"1":[
{"id":"earth1_1","inst":"Look at the solar system.","shape":"solar_system","txt":"Which planet is closest to the Sun?","opts":["Venus","Earth","Mercury"],"cor":2,"exp":"The order from the Sun is: Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune. Mercury is the smallest and closest planet to the Sun."},
{"id":"earth1_2","inst":"Look at the solar system.","shape":"solar_system","txt":"Which is the largest planet in our solar system?","opts":["Saturn","Jupiter","Neptune"],"cor":1,"exp":"Jupiter is by far the largest planet. It is so big that all other planets could fit inside it. It is a gas giant made mostly of hydrogen and helium."},
{"id":"earth1_3","inst":"Look at the rock cycle.","shape":"rock_cycle","txt":"What type of rock is formed when magma or lava cools and solidifies?","opts":["Sedimentary","Metamorphic","Igneous"],"cor":2,"exp":"Igneous rocks form when molten rock (magma underground or lava on the surface) cools and crystallises. Examples: granite (slow cooling, large crystals), basalt (fast cooling, small crystals)."},
{"id":"earth1_4","inst":"Look at the rock cycle.","shape":"rock_cycle","txt":"What turns sedimentary rock into metamorphic rock?","opts":["Melting","Heat and pressure","Weathering"],"cor":1,"exp":"When sedimentary rocks are subjected to extreme heat and pressure deep underground (but not enough to melt them), they change form into metamorphic rocks. Example: limestone becomes marble."},
{"id":"earth1_5","inst":"Look at the water cycle.","shape":"water_cycle","txt":"What process turns liquid water into water vapour?","opts":["Condensation","Precipitation","Evaporation"],"cor":2,"exp":"Evaporation is when liquid water is heated (usually by the Sun) and turns into water vapour (gas). This water vapour rises into the atmosphere."},
{"id":"earth1_6","inst":"Look at the water cycle.","shape":"water_cycle","txt":"What is condensation?","opts":["Water vapour turning into liquid droplets","Liquid water turning into gas","Rain falling from clouds"],"cor":0,"exp":"Condensation is when water vapour (gas) cools and turns back into tiny liquid water droplets. This is how clouds form - water vapour rises, cools, and condenses around dust particles."},
{"id":"earth1_7","inst":"Think about the Earth.","txt":"What causes day and night?","opts":["The Earth orbiting the Sun","The Earth rotating on its axis","The Moon blocking the Sun"],"cor":1,"exp":"The Earth spins (rotates) on its axis once every 24 hours. The side facing the Sun has day, and the side facing away has night."},
{"id":"earth1_8","inst":"Think about seasons.","txt":"Why does the UK have warmer summers?","opts":["The Earth is closer to the Sun in summer","The North Pole is tilted towards the Sun in summer","The Sun is hotter in summer"],"cor":1,"exp":"The Earth's axis is tilted at 23.5 degrees. In summer, the Northern Hemisphere is tilted towards the Sun, so sunlight hits more directly and days are longer, making it warmer."},
{"id":"earth1_9","inst":"Think about space.","txt":"How long does it take for the Earth to orbit the Sun once?","opts":["24 hours","1 month","1 year (365.25 days)"],"cor":2,"exp":"The Earth takes approximately 365.25 days to complete one orbit around the Sun. The extra 0.25 days is why we have a leap year every 4 years."},
{"id":"earth1_10","inst":"Think about the atmosphere.","txt":"Which gas makes up most of the Earth's atmosphere?","opts":["Oxygen","Carbon dioxide","Nitrogen"],"cor":2,"exp":"The atmosphere is about 78% nitrogen, 21% oxygen, and small amounts of other gases including argon and carbon dioxide (only 0.04%)."},
{"id":"earth1_11","inst":"Think about weather.","txt":"What causes wind?","opts":["The Moon's gravity","Differences in air pressure","The Earth spinning"],"cor":1,"exp":"Wind is caused by differences in air pressure. Air moves from areas of high pressure to areas of low pressure. The bigger the difference, the stronger the wind."},
{"id":"earth1_12","inst":"Think about rocks.","txt":"Which type of rock is formed from layers of sediment being compressed over millions of years?","opts":["Igneous","Metamorphic","Sedimentary"],"cor":2,"exp":"Sedimentary rocks form when layers of sediment (small bits of rock, sand, mud, or dead organisms) are deposited and slowly compressed over millions of years. Examples: sandstone, limestone, chalk."}
],"2":[
{"id":"earth2_1","inst":"Think about the Earth's structure.","txt":"The Earth is made of layers. From outside to centre, the correct order is:","opts":["Core, mantle, crust","Crust, mantle, core","Mantle, crust, core"],"cor":1,"exp":"Crust (thin outer layer, 5-70km), Mantle (thick semi-solid layer, about 2900km), Outer Core (liquid iron/nickel), Inner Core (solid iron/nickel, extremely hot)."},
{"id":"earth2_2","inst":"Think about plate tectonics.","txt":"What happens at a destructive plate boundary?","opts":["Plates move apart","One plate is pushed under another","Plates slide past each other"],"cor":1,"exp":"At a destructive boundary, an oceanic plate (denser) is pushed under a continental plate (less dense) in a process called subduction. This can cause earthquakes and volcanoes."},
{"id":"earth2_3","inst":"Think about climate change.","txt":"The greenhouse effect is caused by gases that:","opts":["Block all sunlight from reaching Earth","Trap heat radiation leaving Earth's surface","Create holes in the atmosphere"],"cor":1,"exp":"Greenhouse gases (CO2, methane, water vapour) let sunlight through to warm the Earth, but trap the infrared radiation (heat) that the Earth emits, warming the atmosphere."},
{"id":"earth2_4","inst":"Think about space.","txt":"The Moon causes tides on Earth. How?","opts":["By blowing on the water","By its gravitational pull on the oceans","By reflecting sunlight onto the water"],"cor":1,"exp":"The Moon's gravity pulls on Earth's oceans, creating a bulge of water (high tide) on the side nearest the Moon and another on the opposite side. As Earth rotates, we get two high tides per day."},
{"id":"earth2_5","inst":"Think about fossils.","txt":"Fossils are most commonly found in which type of rock?","opts":["Igneous","Sedimentary","Metamorphic"],"cor":1,"exp":"Fossils form when organisms are buried in sediment that slowly turns to rock. Igneous rock forms from hot magma (destroying any remains), and metamorphic conditions usually destroy fossils too."},
{"id":"earth2_6","inst":"Think about renewable energy.","txt":"Which of these is a renewable energy source?","opts":["Coal","Natural gas","Wind"],"cor":2,"exp":"Wind is renewable - it will not run out. Coal and natural gas are fossil fuels (non-renewable) - they took millions of years to form and are being used up much faster than they form."}
],"3":[
{"id":"earth3_1","inst":"Think about carbon cycle.","txt":"How do fossil fuels contribute to climate change when burned?","opts":["They release stored carbon as CO2","They destroy the ozone layer","They change Earth's orbit"],"cor":0,"exp":"Fossil fuels contain carbon that was stored millions of years ago. Burning them releases CO2 back into the atmosphere, increasing the greenhouse effect and causing global warming."},
{"id":"earth3_2","inst":"Think about space.","txt":"A light-year is a measure of:","opts":["Time","Distance","Speed"],"cor":1,"exp":"A light-year is the DISTANCE that light travels in one year (about 9.46 trillion km). It is used because distances in space are so vast that using km would give impossibly large numbers."},
{"id":"earth3_3","inst":"Think about Earth science.","txt":"What is the theory of plate tectonics?","opts":["The Earth's crust is one solid piece","The Earth's crust is broken into plates that move slowly on the mantle","The Earth's crust is shrinking"],"cor":1,"exp":"Plate tectonics: Earth's crust is broken into large pieces (tectonic plates) that float on the semi-liquid mantle. They move slowly (a few cm/year) causing earthquakes, volcanoes, and mountain formation."}
]};

